{
  "query": "To restore peatlands afforested for commercial forestry, how does simply cutting the trees compare to cutting trees and also rewetting the peat?",
  "relevant_summary": "Eleven studies assessed the combined effects of cutting or removing trees and rewetting the peat. Two site comparison studies in bogs and fens in Finland found that this combination changed the overall plant community composition, making it less like sites that remained drained and forested (1732). The abundance of wetland-characteristic plants was reported to increase in two before-and-after studies in Finland and Sweden (1732). Regarding moss cover, two replicated, paired studies in Sweden and Finland found that the intervention increased Sphagnum cover, while three studies in the UK and Finland noted a reduction in non-Sphagnum or forest-characteristic mosses (1732). Seven studies in the UK, Finland, and Sweden reported an increased cover of herbs like cottongrasses and sedges (1732). Effects on plant species richness were varied, with two studies in rich fens in Sweden showing an increase, while two studies in Finnish fens found no effect (1732). No information was found regarding the effects of solely cutting trees without rewetting.",
  "action_ids": [
    "1732"
  ]
}

